The Law of the Lunar Months

Each lunar month begins on the night when the moon is hidden â€” the New Moon.
That night is Day One. The following day is Day Two, and so forth, until the next New Moon begins a new month.

These months do not have fixed lengths, for the moon herself does not keep to manâ€™s number.
Some months are 29 days, others 30. Thus, the Mirror Sky moves as the Spirit moves â€” with mystery, yet with truth.

Each month is named for the chief star in the constellation the moon enters at her rising.

These are the Twelve Moons of the Mirror Sky:
	1.	Algedes â€“ the horn and burden (Capricorn â€“ Deneb Algedi)
	2.	Sadalmelika â€“ the water bearerâ€™s eye (Aquarius â€“ Sadalmelik)
